            <label class="field-label">Confined Space Entries / Week <span class="tip-icon" data-tip="Number of confined space entry events at your site per week. A bump test before each entry is required by regulation regardless of sensor type. This adds a fixed cost to both scenarios equally; it does not affect the saving calculation.">?</span></label>
            <input type="number" id="confinedSpace" min="0" placeholder="0" oninput="calculate()">
            <div class="field-default">0 = not applicable</div>
          </div>
          <div class="field">
            <label class="field-label">Devices Per Confined Space Entry <span class="tip-icon" data-tip="How many devices are used per confined space entry event, i.e. the crew size. Keeps confined space cost at a site-event level rather than fleet-wide.">?</span></label>
            <input type="number" id="devicesPerCS" min="1" placeholder="e.g. 3" oninput="calculate()">
            <div class="field-default">Typical crew: 2 to 5 devices</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div><!-- /adjust-body -->
    </div><!-- /adjust-panel -->

  </div><!-- /results -->

  <!-- METHODOLOGY -->
  <div class="methodology" style="margin-top:32px">
    <div class="meth-head" onclick="toggleMeth()">
      <div class="meth-head-left">
        <svg class="meth-icon" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path d="M9 4.804A7.968 7.968 0 005.5 4c-1.255 0-2.443.29-3.5.804v10A7.969 7.969 0 015.5 14c1.669 0 3.218.51 4.5 1.385A7.962 7.962 0 0114.5 14c1.255 0 2.443.29 3.5.804v-10A7.968 7.968 0 0014.5 4c-1.255 0-2.443.29-3.5.804V12a1 1 0 11-2 0V4.804z"/></svg>
        <div><div class="meth-title">Calculation Methodology and Scope</div><div class="meth-subtitle">How this calculator works and what it accounts for</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="meth-toggle" id="methLabel">Show <span style="font-size:10px;margin-left:4px">&#9660;</span></div>
    </div>
    <div class="meth-body" id="methBody">
      <h4>What This Calculator Models</h4>
      <p>This calculator helps safety and operations teams quantify the cost of their current gas detection testing regime and compare it against a risk-calibrated alternative based on modern sensor technology.</p>
      <p>It models the <strong>annual cost of routine interval-based bump testing and calibration</strong> for a portable gas detection fleet, comparing your current regime against validated intervals for LEL MPS sensor technology: up to 30-day bump test intervals and up to 180-day calibration intervals under appropriate conditions.</p>
      <p>Costs are calculated across two dimensions: <strong>calibration gas consumption</strong> (cylinder volume, cost, and efficiency-adjusted usable volume per test) and <strong>technician labour</strong> (bump test time and calibration time, derived via a labour time multiplier, applied to event counts and multiplied by fully-loaded hourly rate). Both dimensions use a parallel structure: the user enters a bump test figure and a multiplier determines the calibration figure, for both gas and labour.</p>
      <h4>Prorated Annual Event Counts</h4>
      <p>Annual test counts are calculated as continuous prorated values rather than rounded integers. For example, a 30-day calibration interval applied over 365 calendar days yields 12.17 calibrations per device per year, and this figure is used directly in the cost calculation. The displayed test counts in the results are rounded to whole numbers for readability, which means the visible count may differ slightly from the underlying cost basis. This approach treats the annual figure as an expected-value estimate, which is appropriate for a cost modelling tool used over a full year across a fleet of devices. The methodology note makes this explicit because the displayed numbers look more concrete than they are.</p>
      <h4>Testing Method and Default Assumptions</h4>
      <p>The calculator supports two testing configurations: Manual Testing and Docking Station. Selecting a configuration sets appropriate default values for gas consumed per bump test, the calibration gas multiplier, cylinder efficiency, the bump test time fallback, and the labour time multiplier.</p>
      <p><strong>Manual Testing</strong> defaults reflect a technician using a regulator and hose to bump and calibrate devices individually. Gas per bump test defaults to 0.3L. The calibration gas multiplier defaults to 4x (approximately 1.2L per calibration). Cylinder efficiency defaults to 85%. Bump test time fallback is 3 minutes. Labour time multiplier defaults to 2.5x, reflecting calibrations taking approximately 2.5 times longer than bump tests.</p>
      <p><strong>Docking Station</strong> defaults reflect an automated station with precision metered flow. Gas per bump test defaults to 0.15L. The calibration gas multiplier defaults to 6x (approximately 1L per calibration against a 0.15L bump). Cylinder efficiency defaults to 90%. Bump test time fallback is 1 minute for sequential single-device loading. Labour time multiplier defaults to 3x, reflecting calibration handling taking approximately 3 times longer than bump test handling. For multi-bay stations where devices are loaded simultaneously, the bump test time should be reduced to reflect actual per-device handling time.</p>
      <p>User-entered values for any field override the mode defaults in both configurations.</p>
      <h4>Working Days versus Calendar Days</h4>
      <p>Bump test frequency and calibration frequency are treated on different time bases, because they operate differently in practice. Bump tests are typically performed at shift start, so they follow working days: a daily bump test means one test per working day, and the annual count is driven by how many days per year the site operates. The working days input controls this directly.</p>
      <p>Calibration intervals, by contrast, are always defined in calendar days in every regulatory framework and industry SOP this calculator is designed to support. A 30-day calibration interval means every 30 calendar days regardless of how many of those are working days. The calculator therefore computes annual calibrations as 365 divided by the calibration interval, independent of the working days input. The working days input affects bump test frequency and labour cost only.</p>
      <p>Confined space entry frequency is similarly calendar-based. The calculator uses 52 fixed weeks per year for confined space cost, not a derived working-week count.</p>
      <h4>Cylinder Efficiency Factor</h4>
      <p>Cylinders are never fully exhausted in practice. Gas is lost during regulator connection and purging (typically 0.1–0.3L per connection event), and residual gas cannot be extracted once cylinder pressure drops below the regulator's minimum operating threshold (approximately 10–15% of cylinder volume). The efficiency factor, defaulted to 85%, adjusts the usable cylinder volume to reflect real-world conditions rather than theoretical capacity.</p>
      <h4>Calibration Gas Volume</h4>
      <p>Full calibration events consume more gas than bump tests. The calibration gas multiplier, set in the Advanced Assumptions section, controls this ratio as a multiple of the bump test gas volume.</p>
      <p>For <strong>manual four-gas testing</strong>, a bump test consumes approximately 0.3L and a calibration approximately 1.2L, giving a ratio of 4x. For <strong>docking station testing</strong>, a bump test consumes approximately 0.15L due to precision metered short-duration flow, while a calibration still consumes approximately 1L, giving a ratio of 6x. The docked ratio is higher not because calibration uses more gas in absolute terms, but because docked bump gas consumption is significantly lower, which amplifies the ratio. These figures are based on QA-validated measurements for standard four-gas monitors.</p>
      <p>In standard four-gas monitors, the LEL sensor is the primary driver of bump test and calibration frequency. The catalytic bead LEL sensor can be poisoned by silicones, sulphur compounds, and halogens, and critically it fails silently without alerting the user. This silent-failure risk is the technical basis for the industry-wide daily bump test requirement. MPS sensors do not use a catalyst and cannot be poisoned, removing this failure mode and changing the technical basis for the interval. The O2, H2S, and CO sensors in a four-gas monitor use electrochemical technology that drifts predictably and fails with an alarm signal rather than silently, meaning they do not drive the interval frequency in the same way.</p>
      <p>Single-gas devices should use a lower multiplier, typically 2x to 3x. The field accepts values in 0.5x increments to allow precise adjustment.</p>
      <h4>Confined Space Pre-Entry Testing</h4>
      <p>Confined space pre-entry bump testing is a regulatory requirement in most jurisdictions regardless of sensor type or testing interval. This calculator models confined space testing as a <strong>site-level cost</strong> based on the number of entry events per week and the number of devices used per entry (crew size), applied across 52 calendar weeks per year. This cost is added equally to both scenarios; it does not influence the saving calculation but produces a more accurate total cost picture for sites where confined space work is a regular activity.</p>
      <h4>Eligible Devices and Fleet Composition</h4>
      <p>Scenario B applies the alternative intervals to your entire fleet by default. If you enter a number in the <strong>Devices Eligible for Extended Intervals</strong> field, Scenario B applies the alternative intervals only to those devices. The remaining devices are modelled on your current Scenario A intervals in both scenarios; meaning they contribute equally to both totals and do not distort the saving calculation. The saving reflects only the devices that would genuinely benefit from the technology shift.</p>
      <h4>What Is Excluded</h4>
      <div class="tag-list">
        <span class="tag exc">Post-alarm retesting</span>
        <span class="tag exc">Post over-limit event recalibration</span>
        <span class="tag exc">Post under-limit event testing</span>
        <span class="tag exc">Emergency response testing</span>
        <span class="tag exc">Post-incident return-to-service</span>
        <span class="tag exc">Hydrogen detection environments (NDIR sensors cannot detect hydrogen)</span>
      </div>
      <p style="margin-top:14px">A calculator that claims to model everything invites challenge. One that clearly defines its scope invites trust.</p>
      <h4>What Is Included</h4>
      <div class="tag-list">
        <span class="tag inc">Routine interval bump testing</span>
        <span class="tag inc">Routine interval calibration</span>
        <span class="tag inc">Cylinder gas cost (efficiency-adjusted)</span>
        <span class="tag inc">Technician labour (fully-loaded)</span>
        <span class="tag inc">Retest allowance (if selected)</span>
        <span class="tag inc">Confined space pre-entry testing (additive, crew-based)</span>
      </div>
      <h4>Important Limitations</h4>
      <p>Results are estimates and should be treated as a starting point for internal discussion. Actual savings depend on negotiated gas pricing, specific device and regulator configurations, the mix of sensor types in your fleet, and applicable regulatory requirements in your jurisdiction. This tool does not constitute compliance guidance. Always apply the most stringent requirements applicable to your site and consult your safety officer before modifying any testing SOP.</p>
      <p><strong>Labour cost in docking station environments:</strong> The labour cost model applies bump test time to bump events and calibration time (derived via the labour time multiplier) to calibration events. Both assume sequential single-device handling. In environments with multi-bay stations, technicians load multiple devices simultaneously, so the effective per-device time is a fraction of the single-device figure. Organisations with multi-bay stations should reduce the Time Per Bump Test field to reflect their actual per-device handling time. The gas saving figure is not affected by this limitation.</p>
      <p>This calculator was developed by <strong>Blackline Safety</strong> in collaboration with Nevada Nano, manufacturer of the LEL MPS sensor. It reflects Blackline Safety's point of view on the relationship between sensor diagnostic capability and maintenance interval design.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

